This spec should do the trick:
```json
[
  {
    &quot;operation&quot;: &quot;shift&quot;,
    &quot;spec&quot;: {
      &quot;status&quot;: {
        &quot;*&quot;: {
          &quot;state|moreInfo&quot;: &quot;status.@(1,id).&amp;&quot;
        }
      },
      &quot;users&quot;: {
        &quot;*&quot;: {
          &quot;title&quot;: &quot;users[&amp;1].&amp;&quot;,
          &quot;availability&quot;: {
            &quot;*&quot;: &quot;users[&amp;2].&amp;1[&amp;].id&quot;
          }
        }
      }
    }
  },
  {
    &quot;operation&quot;: &quot;shift&quot;,
    &quot;spec&quot;: {
      &quot;users&quot;: {
        &quot;*&quot;: {
          &quot;title&quot;: &quot;users[&amp;1].&amp;&quot;,
          &quot;availability&quot;: {
            &quot;*&quot;: {
              &quot;id&quot;: {
                &quot;@&quot;: &quot;users[&amp;4].&amp;3[&amp;2].&amp;1&quot;,
                &quot;*&quot;: {
                  &quot;@(6,status.&amp;.state)&quot;: &quot;users[&amp;5].&amp;4[&amp;3].state&quot;,
                  &quot;@(6,status.&amp;.moreInfo)&quot;: &quot;users[&amp;5].&amp;4[&amp;3].moreInfo&quot;
                }
              }
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
]
```
The main idea is to transform the `status` array into a dictionary. To to this, we move the `id` of the status from the array and make it a key.
Check out the [Advanced `@` sign wildcard docs](https://github.com/bazaarvoice/jolt/blob/master/jolt-core/src/main/java/com/bazaarvoice/jolt/Shiftr.java#L324)
The
```json
&quot;*&quot;: {
  &quot;state|moreInfo&quot;: &quot;status.@(1,id).&amp;&quot;
}
```
Says:
&gt; for `state` and `moreInfo` keys of the `*` element put them into the `status` object under the key which is a value stored under the `id` key. 

Moreover, the first shift operation wraps the elements of the `availability` arrays into a json with `id` key for the corresponding value. The title lands in the same place it is now.

After the 1st &quot;shift&quot; operation:
```json
{
  &quot;status&quot; : {
    &quot;online&quot; : {
      &quot;state&quot; : &quot;valid&quot;
    },
    &quot;busy&quot; : {
      &quot;state&quot; : &quot;unknown&quot;
    },
    &quot;any&quot; : {
      &quot;state&quot; : &quot;unknow&quot;,
      &quot;moreInfo&quot; : &quot;unavailable&quot;
    }
  },
  &quot;users&quot; : [ {
    &quot;title&quot; : &quot;foo&quot;,
    &quot;availability&quot; : [ {
      &quot;id&quot; : &quot;online&quot;
    }, {
      &quot;id&quot; : &quot;busy&quot;
    } ]
  }, {
    &quot;title&quot; : &quot;bar&quot;,
    &quot;availability&quot; : [ {
      &quot;id&quot; : &quot;busy&quot;
    }, {
      &quot;id&quot; : &quot;any&quot;
    } ]
  }, {
    &quot;title&quot; : &quot;baz&quot;,
    &quot;availability&quot; : [ {
      &quot;id&quot; : &quot;any&quot;
    } ]
  } ]
}
```


In the second shift operation we use the advanced `@` wildcard again.
We leverage the created `status` dictionary and search for the `state` and `moreInfo` under the desired key equal to the `users.availability.id`

